{"/service/ndnp/vi/batch_vi_doxa_ver01/data/sn94060041/00542866871/1946041201/0266.xml":{"full_text":"Peninsula Enterprise\nAwarded Rhamt- Certificate For Best General Make\nlip and For Rest Handling of Display\nx Advertising\nMember Delmarva Press Association\nFounded By\nJOHN W. KDMONDS\nJune .10. 1881\nALFRKD B. G. EDMONDS\nJOHN W. EDMONDS, Jr.\nOwners and Publishers\nACCOMACK COURT HOUSE, VA.\nentered at the PostofTice at Accomack C. H., Va.,\nas Second-Class Matter\nFRIDAY, APRIL 12, 19:6\nTHE POWER OF TRUTH\n\u201cTruth is mighty and shall prevail,\u2019\u2019 is\nan old saying. Some people doubt it, and\nsay that truth is constantly overthrown. An,\nillustration of the power of truth was given\nin the psychological warfare services which\noperated on behalf of the Allies in World\nWar II.\nIt was the idea of the military authori\nties to tell the truth, and rely on the facts j\nas an influence in breaking the morale of\u2019\nthe enemy. It was not of course possible\nalways to tell the whole truth, but at least\nthe idea was not to tell any falsehoods.\nThe result was the distribution of in\nformation through leaflets, radio, etc. The\ninformation thus given contrasted strongly\nwith the propoganda put out by our\nenemies, which contained so many false\nstatements. The people of the enemy coun\ntries could see that they learned a good deal\nmore about the war from the Allied infor\nmation than they did from their own\nsources. So these services were an import\nant factor in breaking enemy morale.\nThe truth is a mighty power in any\ncountry where there is a free press and\nfree discussion. If falsehoods are written or\nspoken, it is easily possible to expose them,1\nand the result is to discredit the people who\nused them. Thus the free press is a great j\nprotector of the truth, and it makes it i\nvery advisable for contending factions and\nparties to tell the truth.\nEven misstatements of facts, made!\nwithout intention to deceive, react against!\nthe people who issue them, so that it be\ncomes effective in political and economic\ndiscussion not merely to stick to the\ntruth, but to be careful to le accurate in\nthe matters of fact. Political and\neconomic discussion in such a country is\nrarely a controvery between truth and er\nror, but a dispute between different concep\ntions as to justice and fairness. Thus truth\nis proved to be mighty.\nPURPOSEFUL YOUTHS\nIt is remarked concerning G. I.\u2019s who\nhave returned to schools and colleges, that\nthey are as a rule very purposeful and dis\nposed to make the best of their educational\nopportunity. Their war experience has help\ned them to take a serious view of life, and\ntheir return to educational institutions is a\nsign that they fully realize the value of\neducation and want to make the most of\nthese opportunities.\nWhat can be done to instill a more\npurposeful spirit into the minds of some\nyoung people who do not concentrate so well\non their studies? Some old folks who\ncriticize such ones might realize that if\nthey were young again and were confront\ned with the pleasures and enjoyments of\nmodern life, they might show a similar lack\nof concentration.\nThe world today is a fascinating place\nfor boys and girls. The pleasures offered\nare one reason why some do not concentrate\nas they should on their education. There is\nsomething tremendously fascinating about\nthe sports in which they engage. Many are\nthrilled by the idea of acquiring skill at\nthese stunts, and winning the wild applause\nof the crowd and the admiration of the\npublic.\nthen there are the iascinations of the\nmovies and shows and many pastimes. The\nyoung people get interested in the opposite\nsex, and there is the joy of dancing and the\npleasures they have with their automobiles.\nSomehow the mind of youth has to\nlearn not to devote its principal attention\nto these delights, but to concentrate on pre\nparation for life. Young people no doubt are\nmore serious than they were before the\nwar. Recent experiences have made them\nmore purposeful. Most of them realize the\nneed for making the best of education, and\ngetting a good training for the work they\nhave to do in the world.\n\nThe men are looking forward to the\nfishing season, and as usual some who can\nnot walk a short distance to their place of\nbusiness will tramp for miles along some\nbrook.\nHOLY WEEK\nThe week before Easter lias long: been\nobserved as the anniversary of the last\nI week of Jesus\u2019 life. The shadows were\ngathering about the Saviour of mankind on\nthose fateful days, llis sublime words at\nthe Last Supper will forever be treasured\nI as his final message to his followers. j\nj If the world could only have listened\nj to his message delivered on those solemn\ndays, if it could only have followed his lead:\nby manifesting true religian, justice, and\ngenerosity, centuries of suffering and con\nflict could have been avoided. The sacrifice\nof Jesus\u2019 life was a tremendous factor in\nwinning support for his ideas. The sym\npathy and adoration excited by his martyr\ndom drew the attention of the world, and\nwas a great factor in converting many na\ntions to the Christian faith.\n\nGREAT PRODUCTION\nPresident Truman quoted figures a few\ndays ago showing that the current produc\ntion of goods and services for civilian\nmarkets is better than $150,000,000,000 a\nyear. This great output seems to dispose!\nof the fear that the country would run\ninto a serious depression soon after the\nwar.\nAs long as this vast volume of produc\ntion goes on, the people are going to be able\nto buy the output of the factories and\nfarms, and unemployment will be relatively\nlow. There seems no reason why any\ndepressions should come, if the people avoid\nthe dangerous speculation that on some\nformer occasions has brought disaster.\nSome slowing up of industrial activity\nhas occurred in former years because\nexcessive stocks of merchandise were pro\nduced, and business went slow until these\nsurpluses were worked off. Now with s^>\nmany things short or scarce, there seems\nno danger that any such excess can be pro\nduced at present.\nUSE OF MILITARY POWER\nL\u2019p to now the world has been ruled 1\nvery largely by military force. The coun\ntries that had the strongest military power I\nhave been able to largely dominate the'1\nworld. The United Nations Organization was,\nformed to limit the use of military force,\nand get the nations out of the habit of us- j\ning such force for conquest and aggression.\nIt will be a wonderful thing if the na-j\ntions can finally be persuaded to give up1,\nthe idea of using armed forces to conquer\nforeign countries, and as a threat to in-\nfluence their action. It is a difficult thing,\nin a world which has so long been sway- 1\ned by military power, to get this idea es\ntablished. 1\nEven the United States will find that it\nhas to rely on such power to a large extent. 1\nIt will probably want to retain many is\nlands which it captured in the Pacific war\nas a defense against possible aggression,\neven if the inhabitants of some of these\nisland should object. Our country needs\nstrong military power for its own defense.\nSo the time has not yet come when military\npower can be banished from the world.\nsje jjc ?fe\nTOLERANCE BETWEEN NATIONS\nIt will take a lot of tolerance for the\nleading nations in the United Nations\nOrganization to get along together. The\nUnited States and Britain may think Russia\nis not doing just light in the control it still\nmaintains over the small nations next to its\nown territory. Russia may say that Britain\nmaintains military power over lands that\nwant their independence, and that the'\nUnited States will demand the right to\ncontrol many of the island bases it captured\nin the recent war.\nThis is an imperfect world, and perfect\nly correct action cannot be expected of all\nthe nations in it. The main thing is to\npersuade the nations to settle their dis\nputes by peaceful discussion, instead of by\nthe use of military force.\nSPRING FEVER\nAs the spring days steal into our lives\nwith their soft and languid sunshine, rest\nless desire stir the human heart. People\nshut up by the restrictions of winter long\nto get out in the sunshine, and wander\nthrough the fields and observe the revival\nof nature. There is a magnetism in the air\nthat seems to draw us away from the\nburdens of every day life, and which tells\nus to get out and wander.\nNot many are able to satisfy this\ndesire, so people usually settle down to their\nordinary labors with an air of resignation.\nYet the longing persists to quit work, and\ntake life easy in the bright sunshine. These\nfeelings are sometimes referred to as\n\u201cspring fever\u201d, but days usually come when\none can satisfy this longing and get out to\nenjoy the charms of reviving nature.\n\nThey say it is a small world, but\ncome people say it seems large when they\nare trying to find someone who owes them\nmoney.\nChincoteague\nMiss Virginia Birch spent this\nweek in Philadelphia, shopping.\nMrs. Kverette Potts spent a\nfew days in Philadelphia, last\nweek.\nMr. Percy Jones and family\nof Norfolk, spent some time here\nlast week.\nMrs. Frank Bull and Miss Vir\nginia Birch were in Philadelphia\nthis week.\nMrs. Hattie Tarr is visiting herj\ndaughter, Mrs. John Ballerina, in\nPhiladelphia.\nMrs. Herbert Buckalew and\nchildren are guests of her sister\nin Cambridge.\nMr. and Mrs. Francis Ross are\nreceiving congratulations on the\nbirth of a son.\nMr. and Mrs. Milton Jones and\ndaughter, Mary Ann, are visiting\nin Philadelphia.\nMr. A. L. Conant, of Norfolk,\nspent some time here with rela\ntives last week.\nMr. and Mrs. Lloyd Reed, of\nOcean City, spent the week-end\nhere with relatives.\nThe girls Hi-Y held a buffet\nsupper for the Mothers and\nDaughters on April 3.\nMr. W. A. Wimbrough, who has\nbeen ill for the past week, is\nable to be out again.\nMrs. Lula Wimbrow attended\nthe funeral of Mrs. Mima Scott\nin Milton, Del. this week.\nMessrs. William Hudson and\nJulian White spent some time\nthis week in Philadelphia.\nMr. and Mrrs. Wilbur Hurdle,\nof Berlin, were guests Sunday of\nMr. and Mrs. Barnard Hurdle.\nMrs. Miles Hancock is a patient\nin Peninsula Hospital, Salisbury'.\nShe is reported improving nicely.\nMr. and Mrs. Chester Daisey\nand Mr. and Mrs. Carey Daisey\nspent some time in Norfolk, last\nweek.\nMr. and Mrs. Curtis Cluff are\nentertaining their daughter, Mrs.\nHenry Ackerman, of New York!\nCity.\nMrs. Irene Reynolds spent last j\nweek in Philadelphia, as the guest j\nof Mr. and Mrs. William Nes-;\nmith.\nMrs. Charles Collins, Mrs. A.\nJ. Wimbrow and Mrs. Rick Sav\nage spent Tuesday in Norfolk,\nshopping.\nMrs. David Lewis is visiting\nher daughter and family, Rev. and\nMrs. Joseph Dickerson, in Cam\nbridge, Md.\nMr. Howard Clark had as his\nguests recently his fiancee, Miss\nMargaret Ogden, and mother, of\nPhiladelphia.\nMrs. Weldon Harris spent the\nweek-end in Norfolk with Mr.\nHarris, who is stationed there in\nthe Coast Guard.\nMr. and Mrs. Stanley Jackson\nhave moved here from Salisbury.\nMrs. Jackson will be remembered\nas Miss Naomi Hill.\nMr. and Mrs. John Cox have\nreturned to Altoona, Pa., after\nspending a week with Mr. and\nMrs. George Colona.\nMrs. Henry Ackermann, of New\nYork City is spending some time\nas the guest of her parents, Mr.\nand Mrs. Curtis Cluff.\nThe Past Matron and Past Pa\ntrons Club will meet April 26\nwith Mrs. Newman Conant at her\nhome on Main street.\nMiss Margaret Mears, of An\nnapolis, Md., spent the week-end\nin the home' of her parents, Mr.\nand Mrs. J. T. Mears.\nMr. and Mrs. Walter Conley, of\nJenkins Bridge, spent Sunday af\nternoon with their mother, Mrs.\nJ. S. Johnson, who is sick.\nMr. and Mrs. Thomas Sleigh\nand Mr. and Mrs. Wilbur Howard\nhave returned home, after spend\ning some time in Florida.\nEmerson Liscum of the U. S.\nCoast Guard, who has been serv\ning on foreign duty for the past\nseveral months has returned.\nMr. Richard Carpenter, who\nhas spent the winter in Florida,\nhas returned to the home of his\ndaughter, Mrs. Elijah Jester.\nMr. and Mrs. George Wood\nward, of Woodbury, N. J., spent\nlast week as guests of her par\nents, Mr. and Mrs. Al. Lewis.\nMiss Elaine Leonard and Janice\nConant have returned to school\nin Richmond, after spending a\nshort vacation with their parents.\nMr. John Lingo, Sr., and son\nand daughter-in-law, Mr. and Mrs.\nJohn Lingo, Jr., visited his sis\nter, Mrs. Charles Beebe, recently.\nMr. Winfred Booth and daugh\nter, Susanne, of Seaford, Del.,\nwere week-end guests of his fath\ner, Mr. Frank Booth, and sisters.\nMr. A. J. Hill, of Norfolk, Va.,\nspent the week-end here as the\nguest of his daughter and family,\nMayor and Mrs. Henry Leonard.\nMrs. Irving Bowden has re\nturned to her home in Statesville,\nN. t\\, after a visit with her hus\nband\u2019s parents, Mr. and Mrs. C. J.\nBloxom, on North Main street.\nThose attending the funeral of\nMrs. William Scott in Milton,\nDel., Tuesday were, Rev. O. W.\nSawyer, and Mrs. Wilbur Wim\nbrow.\nMrs. Rick Savage and sons,\nRicky and Billy, spent last week\nin Seaford, Del., as the guests of\nher sister, Mrs. Robert Gillis, and\nMr. Gillis.\nMessrs. Carl Taylor, Floyd\nMason and Wilson Thornton made\na business trip to New York last i\nweek in the interest of the Fire\nCompany.\nMr. and Mrs. Caleb Reiner and\nBill Tally, of Atlantic City, N.\nJ., visited Mr. and Mrs. Ernest j\nJones at their home on Main i\nstreet, recently. j\nMiss Elizabeth Sawyer, regis\ntered nurse of Peninsula Hospital,\nSalisbury, spent the week-end1\nwith her parents, Rev. and Mrs. j\nO. W. Sawyer.\nMr. and Mrs. Robert Gillis, of1\nSeaford, Del., spent the week-end!\nwith their parents Mr. and Mrs. j\nE. L. Wimbrow and Mr. and Mrs.\nWilliam Stockley.\nMr. and Mrs Allen Quillen and\ndaughter, of Onancock, spent\nSunday with their parents, Mr.\nand Mrs. Brattie Sharplej' and\nother relatives here.\nEns. Gene Holloway, of the U.\nS. Merchant Marine and Donald\nHolloway of the U. S. Army, are\nspending a furlough with their\nparents, Mr. and Mrs. John Hol\nloway.\nMr. Warren W. Sears, who has!\nbeen stationed here in the Coast\nGuard for several years, has re\nceived an honorable discharge and\nreturned to his home in Concord,\nNorth Carolina.\nEdward Savage, of the U. S.\nCoast Guard, is receiving treat\nment at the Marine Hospital in\nPhiladelphia. Mrs. Savage is\nspending some time in Philadel\nphia, during his stay.\nMr. and Mrs. Harvey Magee\nare receiving congratulations on\nthe birth of a daughter in Penin\nsula Hospital, Salisbury. Mrs.\nMagee will be remembered as\nMiss Juliette Thornton.\nMr. Delmas Bowden, of Phila\ndelphia and Mrs. Ethel Andrews.\nMrs. Emma Bowden and Mrs.\nEllen Davis visited in the home\nof Mrs. William Hutchinson in\nHarborton, Va., recently.\nMr. Raymond Russell has re\nturned to New York, where he is\nstationed in the Coast Guard, af\nter spending some time with his\nwife in the home of his parents,\nMr. and Mrs. John Russell.\nMr. William Scott was called\nto the home of his daughter in\nMilton, Del. last week on account\nof the illness and death of his\nwife. Mrs. Scott was taken ill\nand died while visiting there.\nMrs. Carlton Collins and son,\nCarlton, Jr., Mrs. Baynard Jester\nand little daughter, Mrs. Elva\nJester and Mrs. Esley Justice and\nMrs. L. D. Justice shopped in\nParksley and Onancock, Thursday.\nMrs. Annie Wilson, of George\ntown, Del., Mrs. George Cord\ndry, Mrs. Ralph Chapman and\nMiss Hattie Williams, of Snow\nHill, were visitors in the home\nof Mrs. R. G. Phipps, Sunday af\nternoon.\nMiss Helen Watson, daughter\nof' Mr. and Mrs. Arthur J. Wat\nson, of Chincoteague, Va., who\nis a student at Shenandoah Con\nservatory of Music, is spending\nher spring vacation with her\nparents.\nThe W. S. C. S., of Christ\nMethodist Church will hold a\nkitchen shower in the Church\nCommunity House for the Com\nmunity House. Refreshments will\nbe served and an interesting pro\ngram will be rendered.\nMrs. Maude Carpenter is the\nguest of her brother-in-law and\nsister, Mr. and Mrs. J. T. Jamie\nson, of Upper Darby, Pa., after\nattending the wedding of her\nniece the former Miss Nellie\nFlorence Prettyman in Bellaire,\nOhio.\nA musical comedy to be pro\nduced by the Juniors and Seniors\nof the Chincoteague High School\nwill be presented April 26, 1946\nat eight o\u2019clock. If you want a\ngood laugh, enjoy good singing,\nand like clean fun, come out Fri\nday night. Admission 40 cents.\nMr. and Mrs. Elic Justice en\ntertained their son and wife, Mr.\nand Mrs. J. William Justice, and\nfriends, Mr. and Mrs. William\nMitchell, of Exmore, Sunday at\ntheir home on North Main street.\nThey also entertained their grand\nson Mr. Woodston Mears and\nwife.\nEastern Shore Fire\nIns. Co. Celebrates\n40th Birthday\nContinued from page 1\nKastville, acting as toastmaster\nintroduced the speakers. There\nwere several talks, the main\nspeaker being W. R. Goffigon, of\nCape Charles. Music was furnish\n1 ed by Mrs. Reide Onley and!\nOnancock High School students.\nGeorge W. Gillespie gave a\nbrief history of the company from\nits organization, listing the origin\nal directors and their successors\nfrom time to time. The original\nboard when it was organized in\n1!>06 had twenty members. Of the\ntwenty, only two are living Mr.\nFrank B. Bell, of Machipongo, who\nhas served continuously since the\ncompany was organized and Mr.\nSmith K. Martin, of Harborton.\nwho was a member of the original\nboard, but resigned after serving\nthe first year. Both were present\nfor the banquet. The first policy\nissued by the company was to\nSmith K. Martin, of Harborton,\nfor $500 on a two story frame,\nshingle' roof dwelling, occupied by\na colored tenant.\nThe original directors of the\ncompany were: Solomon T. John\nson, William L. Nock, C. W. Fed\ndeman, John H. Hopkins, John W.\nBowdoin, J. W. Barnes, Dr. J. H.\nAyres, J. S. Bull L. Floyd Nock,\nFrancis S. Smith, S. K. Martin, S.\nW. Ames, S. D. Rulon, J. W.\nChandler, P. B. Tankard, Dr. J.\nT. Wilkins, Frank B. Bell, Otho\nF. Mears, L. J. Whitehead, W.\nM. Upshur and R. D. L. Fletcher.\nThe following have been direct\nors of the company in adidtion to\nthe original directors: H. T.\nWhite, E. T. Powell, Thos W.\nBlackstone, J. H. Jones, Dr. W.\nL. Dalby, J. C. Walker, George\nF. Nock, S. S. Wilkins, Warner\nAmes, Wm. T. Mason, Judge N.\nB. Weseott, Ben T. Gunter, J. T.\nWilkins, III, W. E. Hutchinson\nand Dr. Wr. F. Kellam.\nThe company now has total as\nsets of $423,982.99 as against total\nassets of $79,217.63 in 1911. Its\nincome in 1945 was $104,679.33.\nNet losses in 1945 were $21,913.\n43. The capital of the company\nis $104,100. and surpluse $219,\n269. 09.\nAlbert M. Hutch\ninson Drowns Fri\nday Afternoon\nContinued From Page 1\nwas in Onancock Cemetery. The\nactive pallbearers were: Messrs.\nPercy C. Ayres, Maurice Adams,\nHenry L. Parks, G. B. West,\nErnest James and Roger J. Hutch\ninson; Honorary\u2014Messrs. N. B.\nReade, H. L. Williams, J. R. Bull,\nR. R. Hutchinson, R. M. Hutch\ninson, C. O. Bonniwell, R. S.\nMathias, F. E. Nicolls, John T.\nHutchinson, L. F. Beasley, C. R.\nHutchinson, S. K. Martin, M. R.\nHutchinson, Harold Harrison, L.\nI. Agathoin, C. R. Taylor, Jr.,\nL. F. Nock, A. Q. Mears, Frank\nlin Hill, Sam Brimer, Norwood\nSrockett, D. C. Butler, Jimmv\nDize, Costin Crockett, G. A. Bon\nniwell, Herbert Hutchinson, Nick\nStaunas, John A. Evans, H. E.\nBenjamin, Eddie Buck Boggs and\nG. C. Buggs.\nHe is survived by his mother,\nMrs. Wm. E. Hutchinson, a\ndaughter, Miss Mary J. Hutchin\nson, of Keller, and two sisters,\nMrs. Kirk Bowers, of Kansas\nCity, Missouri, and Mrs. Roland\nBugg, of Alta Vista, Va.\nIn The Service\nCharles E. Whealton, Jr., yeo\n.man first class, was honorably\ndischarged from the United States\nNaval Reserve, at Naval Person\nnel Separation Center, Camp\nShelton, Norfolk, Virginia, on\nMarch 21, 1946. Mr. Whealton\nvoluntarily enlisted December 7,\n1942.\nPvt, Oscar L. Bundick, Jr., now\nin the armed forces, has received\na certificate of completion of\ncourse entitled \u201cSpecialists Train\ning\u201d on automotive maintenance\nfrom the Army Service Forces\nTraining Center at Fort Belvoir,\nVirginia. He is the son of Mr. and\nMrs. Oscar Bundick, of Accomack.\nMr. and Mrs. W. A. Wimbrough\ncelebrated their birhtday on Sun\nday, March 31, with a birthday\ndinner at their home on Willow\nstreet. Those present were Mrrs.\nPearl Matthews, of Salisbury;\nMr. and Mrs. Ben Bunting, and\nMr. and Mrs. Ernest Darby, of\nAssawoman.\nWord was received here thif\nweek of the death of Mrs. Mima\nScott, wife of Mr. William Scott,\nof Assateague Beach, who passed\naway at the home of her daugh\nter, Mrs. William Collins, of Mil\nton, Del. Her funeral was held\nat the Wilson Funeral Home in\nMilton, Tuesday afternoon. We\nextend heartfelt sympathy to the\nbereaved family.\nftVARM NEWS\n1946 Sweet Potato Support Price\nThe U. S. Department of Agri\nculture recently announced the\nsupport price that will he in effect\nfor the 1946 crop of sweet pota\ntoes. The operations outlined and\nthe schedule of prices given are\ndesigned to support a price to\ngrowers of not less than 90 per\ncent of parity. The price support\nannouncement provides for pur\nchases from September 1 through\nNovember 15. After November 15,\n1946 and continuing through\nJanuary 15, 1947, loans will he\navailable. From January 1 through\nApril 15 settlement will be made\non loans.\nThe program for the 1946 sweet\npotato crop differs in some major\nrespects from the programs in ef\nfect for the past two years. In the\nfirst place, purchases will be\nmade only from September 1\nthrough November 15 and at an\nnounced prices, while last year\npurchase prices for this period\nwere not announced in advance.\nAnother major difference is that\nloans on cured sweet potatoes\nwill be made on ungraded lots\nprovided they contain an average\nof not less than 50 per cent U.\nS. No. 1 quality, and are stored\nin rigid containers in approved\nstorage. Formerly the loan rates\nwere based on a graded and pack\ned for shipment basis. Consequent\nly, the loan rates for the 1946\ncrop are lower than in previous\nyears. In addition, loans will be\nmade only from November 15\nthrough January 15 and loan set\ntlement will be made from Novem\nber 15 through December 31 only\non those lots showing actual or\nthreatened deterioration neces\nsitating immediate disposal. From\nJanuary 1 through April 15, loan\nsettlements will be made at prices\nset forth in the attached schedule.\nAnother important change from\nlast season is that the maximum\nloan and purchase prices will ap\nply only to the I\u2019orto Rican, Nancy\nHall, Jersey, Golden, Triumph, and\nother varieties of similar charac\nteristics. Varieties other than\nthese will be supported, but at\nlower prices.\nWhile the announced price at\nwhich purchases will be made are\nfor sweet potatoes packed in\nspecified containers f. o. b. cars\nor trucks in carload lots, provision\nis made for purchase in bulk at\nlower prices, reflecting the ap\nproximate saving in container and I\nhandling costs.\nThe minimum grade for which\nsupport prices are announced is\nU. S. No. 1. The support price for\nj this grade is $1.15 per bushel.\nA specified grade better than\ni U. S. No. 1 will be supported at\n$1.40 per bushel. The specifica\ntions for this grade will be that\nthey must be U. S. No. 1 grade\nwhich in addition are fairly clean\nand at least an average of 60 per\ncent by weight are fairly well\nshaped. The above support prices\non green sweet potatoes shall a_p\nply from September 1 through\nNovember 15. The program an\nnounced today does not carry any\nadvance announcement for USD A\nsupport of grades below U. S. No.\n1, nor does it imply support for\nthese lower grades at fixed prices\nor fixed relationships to the\nprices for U. S. No. 1. However,\nif it bspomes necessary, in order\nto carry out the Department\u2019s\nprice support obligations price\nlevels, terms and conditions for\nsupporting the lower grades will\nthen be announced.\nCritical Food Situation\nHousewives of Accomack Coun\nty today were given nine ways in\nwhich they can help to save food\nto save starving Europeans by\nBen P. Paradee, County Manager\nof the Emergency food program\nfor the United States Department\nof Agriculture.\nIn suggesting concrete ways in\nwhich each household may assist\nin accumulating the huge food\nsupplies needed in the current\ndesperate needs of the world,\nManager Ben P. Paradee made it\nclear that the over-all needs of the\nwar-torn world for food are so\ngreat there is no limit to the\nAmerican food that can be used\nto save human life.\nMain emphasis falls on the\nconservation of wheat, fats and\noils, Mr. Paradee indicated. These\nbase commodities are the most es\nsential to healthful minimum diet\nand represent the absolute mini\nmum needs.\nThe following are the recom\nmendations made today by the\nCounty Emergency Food Program\nManager:\n1. Cut down on the wastage of\nbread in every way possible.\nPresent estimates are to the ef\nfect that 5 per cent or one slice\nout of every loaf of bread baked\nevery day does into the garbage\ncan.\n2. Reduce the amount of bread\nused at each meal through substi\ntutes such as potatoes, and oat\ncereals. Use fruits, for example,\ninstead of cakes and pastries for\ndesserts.\nti. By the use of alternate foods,\nuse less wheat cereals for break\nfast.\n\u25a01. Save cooking oils by making\nK. M. A. Gal 2\nmore extensive use of meat drip\npings for cooking and seasoning\nfood.\n5. Hold down the number of\nfried foods that are served.\nSave an re-use fats and\noils for all cooking purposes.\n7. Hold on to bacon grease for\ncooking and render excess fats on\nmeats.\n8. All fats that cannot be re\nused should be salvaged and turn\ned in to the butcher or grocer.\n9. Take it easy on oils and\nsalad dressings.\n\u201cIf every housewife in Accomack\ncounty would take these recom\nmendations to heart and practice\nthem, the United States could\ncome a lot closer to meeting the\nexpectations of the starving na\ntions,\u201d Mr. Paradee commented.\n\u201cHere are ways in which eacli of\nus can take a direct part in one of\nthe greatest and most humani\ntarian life-saving crusades ever\nlaunched.\u201d\nThe County Emergency Food\nCouncil is drawing up a similar\nlist of suggestions for the owners\nof public eating places and the\nfood distribution trade and will\nrelease them in the near future,\nMr. l'aradee commented.\nProprietors of public eating\nplaces, with the cooperation of\ntheir customers, can put into ef\nfect immediate economies that will\nmean life to countless thousands\nof persons otherwise doomed to\ndeath, Ben P. Paradee, County\nmanager of the National\nEmergency food Program, said\ntoday in announcing a serise of\nspecific actions which restaurants,\nhotels, and other eating places\nmay adopt to save food needed\nabroad.\nThe list of food saving\nmeasures that may be taken by\npublic eating places supplements\na previous list of consumer food\neconomies announced by Mr. Para\ndee. Both suggestions have been\nsupported by the President\u2019s\nFamine Emergency Committee.\n\u201cIf we as a people are to be of\nthe greatest help to the world in\nthis life-or-death crisis, each of us\nmust make the saving of food his\nor her personal responsibility,\u201d\nMr. Paradee asftrted. \u201cThe food\nwill not create itself. Our farm\ners produce it, but all of us as\nconsumers must take an immediate\ninterest in seeing that as much of\nour abundance as possible is\nshared with those in dire need.\u201d\nThe following are the recom\nmendations placed before the res\ntaurant owners of Accomack\nCounty.\n1. Drop the use of toast as a\ngarnish with meat, poultry and\noff dishes.\n2. Cut out the practice of put\nting baskets of bread or rolls on\ndining room tables. A single roll\nor slice of bread should be served\nwith more forthcoming only on re\nquest of the patron.\n3. Where possible, use the open\nfaced sandwich in place of the\ntwo-bread-slice sandwich.\n4. Don\u2019t trim toast or sandwich\ncrusts.\n5. Use potatoes instead of\nwheat and rice garnishes.\n6. Bake single instead of\ndouble-crust pies.\n7. Substitute corn and buck\nwheat cakes for wheat cakes\nwhere possible.\n8. Instead of products made\nfrom wheat, serve oatmeal bread,\ncakes and cookies.\n9. Reduce the size of rolls and\nbread.\n10. Use fruits and gelatin des\nserts for pastries and cakes.\n11. Serve fewer crackers with\nsoups and cheese.\n12. Discontinue the baking of\nthree-layer cakes for the duration.\n13. Use boiled\u2014instead of oil\u2014\ndressings on salads.\n14. Instead of wheat cereals,\nuse alternates where possible.\n15. In the kitchen, practice the\nre-use of food fats where pos\nsible and salvage grease.\n16. Think up and use methods\nof saving the bread ends now\nwasted.\n17 Boil or broil\u2014not fry\u2014fish\nto save fats.\n18. Don\u2019t serve extra dressing\nwith salad already prepared with\noil or dressing.\n19. On every possible occasion,\ninduce the customer to order only\nwhat he needs.\nCustomers should be encouraged\nto ask only for those side dishes\nthey really want to eat..\nThe Face Of Famine\nTree bark, weeds, cottonseed\nContinued on page 8","height":"26216","width":"20484"}}
